For this to work a VideoView needs to be added to the Activity like this

base.OnCreate(bundle);
Game1.Activity = this;
var g = new Game1();
FrameLayout fl = new FrameLayout(this);  
fl.AddView(g.Window);  
VideoView videoView = new VideoView(this); 
videoView.Id = MonoGame.Android.Media.VideoViewId;
var layoutParams = new ViewGroup.LayoutParams(ViewGroup.LayoutParams.FillParent,ViewGroup.LayoutParams.FillParent); 
fl.AddView(videoView, layoutParams);
SetContentView(fl);  
g.Run();

Platform: Windows 7 64bits

Calling the following code before calling Game.Run() had no effect, the window is always 640x480.

```
graphics = new GraphicsDeviceManager(this);
graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 1280;
graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 720;
graphics.SynchronizeWithVerticalRetrace = true;
graphics.IsFullScreen = false;
graphics.ApplyChanges();
```

Calling it a bit afterwards, once the run loop is going on, works as expected.

Looks like OpenTKGameWindow receives an OnResize event at the start that overrides all previously set sizes.

I don't know if my patch is correct but without my changes this won't work:

```
var texture = Content.Load<Texture2D>("my_texture");
var data = new Color[texture.Width * texture.Height];

texture.GetData(data);
texture.SetData(data); // throws a null reference exeption
```
